subsection.p:
First, in Figure, we consider points P, Q, and R where Q results from traversing 1/8 of the circumference from P, and R 1/8 of the circumference from Q.  In particular, we note that the distance d_1 along the circle from P to Q is the same as the distance d_2 along the circle from Q to R, and thus d_1 = d_2.  At the same time, it is apparent from the geometry of the circle that the change in height h_1 from P to Q is greater than the change in height h_2 from Q to R, so h_1 \gt h_2.  Thus, we can say that

	AV_{[P,Q]} = \frac{h_1}{d_1} \gt \frac{h_2}{d_2} = AV_{[Q,R]} 
.
